{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 09:49:30.438249", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — RIP mini-Internet + WireGuard VPN overlay\n\nScope and tests performed\n- Verified general reachability across the lab (bulk reachability probe).\n- Targeted ICMP tests from host_1 and host_2 to VPN server and to the two web servers (web_server_1_1, web_server_1_2).\n- Performed an HTTP (curl) test to web_server_1_1 from host_1.\n- Collected FRR running configurations from router1, router2, gateway_router, external_router_1.\n- Inspected host network stacks for host_1, host_2 and vpn_server_1 (ifconfig/ip addr/ip route).\n\nHigh-level summary\n- Data-plane connectivity between internal hosts and external web servers is healthy. ICMP tests show 0% packet loss and low RTTs across the measured paths. HTTP access to web_server_1_1 from host_1 succeeded with very low latency.\n- The WireGuard VPN overlay is present (wg0 interfaces are UP on both client and server) but shows no packets transmitted/received — the tunnel is apparently not carrying traffic. Despite that, internal hosts can reach the web servers directly via the normal routed path (i.e., not via the tunnel).\n- There is an FRR configuration oddity on gateway_router — a malformed/placeholder \"network None\" statement under the RIP section. The routing table on gateway_router, however, does show learned RIP routes for both 10.0.x and 20.0.x prefixes.\n\nDetailed findings and evidence\n\n1) Reachability and performance\n- Bulk reachability: All active host -> web server ping tests returned 0% loss (get_reachability output). Examples:\n  - Many hosts (host_1, host_2, vpn_server_1, web servers) -> web_server_1_1/web_server_4_8 all reported 0% loss and RTTs of a few milliseconds.\n- Targeted pings:\n  - host_1 -> vpn_server_1 (20.0.0.2): 4/4, 0% loss, rtt avg = 2.447 ms.\n  - host_1 -> web_server_1_1 (20.0.0.3): 4/4, 0% loss, rtt avg = 2.625 ms.\n  - host_1 -> web_server_1_2 (20.0.0.4): 4/4, 0% loss, rtt avg = 2.826 ms.\n  - host_2 analogous pings also 0% loss.\n- HTTP test:\n  - host_1 -> http://20.0.0.3 (4 requests) — very small total times (examples: 0.0055, 0.0019, 0.00216, 0.00193 s). Web service responds and is reachable.\n\nInterpretation: The normal routed path from internal hosts through the gateway to external_router/web servers is functional and carries traffic reliably.\n\n2) WireGuard tunnel status (VPN overlay)\n- host_1 ifconfig/wg0:\n  - wg0 present and UP, configured with 172.16.1.11/24\n  - RX packets 0 bytes 0, TX packets 0 bytes 0\n  - ip route shows 172.16.1.0/24 via wg0\n- vpn_server_1 ifconfig/wg0:\n  - wg0 present and UP, configured with 172.16.1.1/24\n  - RX packets 0 bytes 0, TX packets 0 bytes 0\n- Despite the tunnel devices being UP on both ends, there is no WireGuard traffic (no packets on wg0 on either side).\n- However, host_1 can reach web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2 over IP (20.0.0.x) and get HTTP responses — so traffic is flowing over the normal routed infrastructure rather than the VPN data plane.\n\nInterpretation: The WireGuard control/data plane is not carrying packets (no handshakes/data) even though logical interfaces are present. VPN endpoints respond to ICMP on their 20.0.0.x addresses, but the encrypted tunnel is not being used for traffic (or not established).\n\n3) FRR/RIP configuration and routing\n- router1 config: router rip networks include 192.168.0.0/16 and 10.0.0.0/24.\n- router2 config: router rip networks include 192.168.0.0/16 and 10.0.1.0/24.\n- external_router_1 config: router rip networks include 192.168.0.0/16 and 20.0.0.0/24.\n- gateway_router config: router rip shows \"network 192.168.0.0/16\" and strangely \"network None\" (malformed/placeholder).\n  - This \"network None\" is an anomalous configuration line and is not normally expected.\n- gateway_router routing table (show ip route) shows learned RIP routes for:\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 through 192.168.0.56 (eth0)\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 through 192.168.0.58 (eth1)\n  - 20.0.0.0/24 via 192.168.0.60 (eth2)\n  - Other 20.0.x/24 networks via respective ethX\n  - Many /31 inter-router subnets are present as learned routes; connected /31s are present on the gateway.\n- The routing table indicates route exchange is functioning and traffic is forwarded appropriately through gateway_router to external_router_1 and the bridged web server LANs.\n\nInterpretation: RIP is operating effectively (routes are present and consistent). The \"network None\" entry in gateway_router FRR config stands out as misconfiguration but has not (in observable tests) prevented route dissemination or reachability.\n\nAnomalies, localization, and likely root cause(s)\n\nAnomaly A — VPN overlay not carrying traffic (primary anomaly)\n- Symptom: wg0 interfaces on both the client (host_1) and server (vpn_server_1) are UP but show 0 RX/TX packets.\n- Evidence: host_1 ifconfig/wg0 shows RX/TX 0; vpn_server_1 wg0 shows RX/TX 0.\n- Effect: Encrypted overlay is not being used; traffic to the web servers is taking the normal routed path instead of the intended WireGuard tunnel.\n- Localization: The problem is localized to the WireGuard overlay endpoints (host_1 and vpn_server_1) or to the WireGuard pairing/handshake between them. The IP connectivity between the endpoints (20.0.0.x addresses) is alive — pings succeed — so the issue is specific to WireGuard establishment/allowed-ips/peering, not basic IP reachability.\n- Likely root cause (inferred from evidence): WireGuard peers have not established handshakes / allowed-ips or peer endpoint settings prevent tunnel traffic (i.e., data plane handshake is not occurring). The presence of wg0 interfaces but zero counters suggests the peer relationship or WireGuard keys/peer config/allowed-ips are incorrect or there is no traffic matching the tunnel's allowed-ips, so no encapsulated packets traverse the devices.\n\nAnomaly B — FRR configuration oddity on gateway_router\n- Symptom: gateway_router FRR running-config shows \"network None\" under router rip.\n- Evidence: frr_show_running_config output for gateway_router contains:\n  - router rip\n    network 192.168.0.0/16\n    network None\n- Effect: This is a configuration anomaly (syntactically/semantically incorrect entry). Despite this, the gateway_router routing table shows expected RIP routes and connected interfaces; route exchange appears functional.\n- Localization: The anomaly is in the gateway_router configuration file (FRR).\n- Likely root cause (inferred): A misconfigured FRR network statement (possibly a templating error or incorrect network declaration) — it has not visibly disrupted routing in the current snapshot, but it is an abnormal config that could cause issues under other conditions.\n\nImpact assessment\n- Service reachability: Web servers (including web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2) are reachable from internal hosts (host_1, host_2) via the regular routed infrastructure. HTTP works and pings are successful — so service availability is unaffected in observed tests.\n- Security/segmentation: The VPN overlay intended to provide an encrypted path to those web servers is not being used. If the design expectation is that those web servers should only be accessible via the VPN, the current state is a policy/security gap: hosts can reach them directly without using the encrypted tunnel.\n- Stability/routing: RIP and forwarding appear stable and functioning based on the route table and reachability tests.\n\nConclusions (diagnostic)\n- The data-plane routing of the underlying network (FRR/RIP, router interconnects, web server LANs) is healthy and forwarding traffic as expected.\n- The WireGuard VPN overlay is not functioning as a data plane — wg0 interfaces are present but carry no traffic; the tunnel is not established/used. This is the primary abnormal behavior.\n- There is a FRR configuration oddity on gateway_router (\"network None\") that looks like a misconfiguration. It has not broken reachability in the current tests but is an abnormal config item that should be reviewed.\n- Root cause (summary):\n  - VPN: Tunnel peer establishment/configuration issue (WireGuard handshake/peer/allowed-ips or peer endpoint specifics) — causing no encrypted traffic on wg0 on client and server.\n  - FRR gateway config: misconfigured network statement on gateway_router (likely a configuration/templating error).\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- Show WireGuard peer status (wg show) and logs on host_1 and vpn_server_1 to confirm handshake/state details (to further narrow the VPN root cause).\n- Show more FRR/RIP status (show ip rip database/neighbors) to analyze whether the \"network None\" has any runtime effect.\n(Do not proceed with remediation unless you request it.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 17087, "output_tokens": 3949, "total_tokens": 21036, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16000}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1792}}}
